{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636932"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:36:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:36:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17617"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17617"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.64,0,0.04,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79487"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10331"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64809"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6657"},{"type":"tags","id":"6658"},{"type":"tags","id":"6670"},{"type":"tags","id":"11263"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26011"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79487"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe facial artery provides important blood supply to structures of the face.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the course of the facial artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Passes through the parotid gland before reaching the face","Emerges at angle of mandible and courses anterior to masseter","Enters the face through the mental foramen","Courses deep to the mandible throughout its path","Emerges posterior to the masseter muscle"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial artery (image) emerges at the angle of the mandible and courses anterior to the masseter muscle\u003C/strong\u003E. It is a branch of the external carotid artery and has a tortuous course as it travels superiorly to supply the nose and upper lip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPasses through the parotid gland\u003C/strong\u003E - The facial artery does not traverse the parotid gland; this is characteristic of the superficial temporal artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnters the face through the mental foramen\u003C/strong\u003E - The mental nerve and vessels exit through the mental foramen, not the facial artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECourses deep to the mandible\u003C/strong\u003E - The facial artery courses superficially over the mandible, not deep to it\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmerges posterior to the masseter muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - The facial artery emerges anterior to the masseter, not posterior\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe facial artery is palpable where it crosses the mandible anterior to the masseter muscle. It provides important blood supply to facial structures including the lips, nose, and cheeks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The facial artery is a branch of the external carotid artery that emerges at the angle of the mandible.","The facial artery courses over the mandible anterior to the masseter muscle.","Terminal branches of the facial artery supply the nose and upper lip."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cAnatomical dissections\u201d by Anatomist90 is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Slide6yyyy.JPG\u003E","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64809"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17617"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21379"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21379"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17cY2K2rJt1kuPPNkctEivz6tTxt2N.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/17cY2K2rJt1kuPPNkctEivz6tTxt2N.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64809"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T20:08:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T20:08:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10331"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79487"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ